Television programs that exploit immigration enforcement as entertainment with
the support and help of government border security agencies are not limited to
Japan.

Media in the [United
Kingdom](https://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1020845/Home-Office-
funds-Sky-propaganda-400-000-taxpayers-money.html) and
[Australia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Border_Security:_Australia%27s_Front_Line)
have long broadcast programs in which travelers and undocumented migrants are
ambushed, interrogated, detained and sometimes deported on camera.

A similar [Canadian
program](https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2016/06/12/border-
security-tv-show-cancelled-after-watchdog-finds-privacy-violation.html),
produced with the direct cooperation of the Canada Border Services Agency
(CBSA), was canceled in 2016 due to personal privacy violations. The program
is still broadcast in [reruns](https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/border-
security-tv-cbsa-1.4805680).

